defs.docs:
The goal of this crate is to provide Rust bindings to the Web APIs and to allow
 a high degree of interoperability between Rust and JavaScript.

defs.name: DiscardOnDrop
defs.docs:
If you have a value which implements [`Discard`](https://docs.rs/discard/%5E1.0.3/discard/trait.Discard.html), you can use
 [`DiscardOnDrop::new(value)`](struct.DiscardOnDrop.html#method.new) which will wrap the value.
 When the wrapper is dropped it will automatically call [`value.discard()`](https://docs.rs/discard/%5E1.0.3/discard/trait.Discard.html#tymethod.discard).

attributes.value:
must_use =
      "

     The DiscardOnDrop is unused, which causes it to be immediately discarded.
     You probably don't want that to happen.

     How to fix this:

       * Store the DiscardOnDrop in a variable or data structure.

       * Or use the leak() method which will cause it to not be
         discarded (this will usually leak memory!)

     See the documentation for more details.
"

defs.name: Date
defs.docs:
[(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date)
 https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-date-constructor

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Creates a JavaScript Date instance that represents a single moment in time.
 Date objects are based on a time value that is the number of milliseconds since 1 January 1970 UTC.

defs.name: from_datetime
defs.value: fn (year: i32, month: i32, day: i32, hours: i32, minutes: i32, seconds: i32, milliseconds: i32) -> Self
defs.docs:
Creates a JavaScript Date instance that represents a single moment in time.
 Date objects are based on a time value that is the number of milliseconds since 1 January 1970 UTC.
 
 year is an integer value representing the year. Values from 0 to 99 map to the years 1900 to 1999.
 month is an integer value representing the month, beginning with 0 for January to 11 for December
 day is an integer value representing the day of the month (normally from 1 to 31)
 hours an integer value representing the minute segment of a time
 seconds an integer value representing the second segment of a time
 milliseconds an integer value representing the millisecond segment of a time

defs.name: from_iso8601
defs.docs:
Creates a JavaScript Date instance that represents a single moment in time.
 Date objects are based on a time value that is the number of milliseconds since 1 January 1970 UTC.
 
 String value representing a date. The string should be in a format recognized by
 the Date.parse() method (IETF-compliant RFC 2822 timestamps and also a version of ISO8601).

defs.name: from_time
defs.docs:
Creates a JavaScript Date instance that represents a single moment in time.
 Date objects are based on a time value that is the number of milliseconds since 1 January 1970 UTC.
 
 Integer value representing the number of milliseconds since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC,
 with leap seconds ignored (Unix Epoch; but consider that most Unix timestamp functions count in seconds).

defs.name: utc
defs.value: fn (year: i32, month: i32, day: i32, hours: i32, minutes: i32, seconds: i32, milliseconds: i32) -> f64
defs.docs:
The Date.UTC() method accepts the same parameters as the longest form of the constructor, and
 returns the number of milliseconds in a Date object since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00, universal time.

defs.name: parse
defs.docs:
The Date.parse() method parses a string representation of a date, and returns the number of
 milliseconds since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC or NaN if the string is unrecognized or, in
 some cases, contains illegal date values (e.g. 2015-02-31).

defs.name: now
defs.docs: The Date.now() method returns the number of milliseconds elapsed since 1 January 1970 00:00:00 UTC.

defs.name: get_date
defs.docs: The getDate() method returns the day of the month for the specified date according to local time.

defs.name: get_day
defs.docs:
The getDay() method returns the day of the week for the specified date according to local time,
 where 0 represents Sunday. For the day of the month see getDate().

defs.name: get_full_year
defs.docs: The getFullYear() method returns the year of the specified date according to local time.

defs.name: get_hours
defs.docs: The getHours() method returns the hour for the specified date, according to local time.

defs.name: get_milliseconds
defs.docs: The getMilliseconds() method returns the milliseconds in the specified date according to local time.

defs.name: get_minutes
defs.docs: The getMinutes() method returns the minutes in the specified date according to local time.

defs.name: get_month
defs.docs:
The getMonth() method returns the month in the specified date according to local time, as a
 zero-based value (where zero indicates the first month of the year).

defs.name: get_seconds
defs.docs: The getSeconds() method returns the seconds in the specified date according to local time.

defs.name: get_time
defs.docs:
The getTime() method returns the numeric value corresponding to the time for the specified
 date according to universal time.

defs.name: get_timezone_offset
defs.docs: The getTimezoneOffset() method returns the time zone difference, in minutes, from current locale (host system settings) to UTC.

defs.name: get_utc_date
defs.docs:
The getUTCDate() method returns the day (date) of the month in the specified date according to
 universal time.

defs.name: get_utc_day
defs.docs:
The getUTCDay() method returns the day of the week in the specified date according to universal
 time, where 0 represents Sunday.

defs.name: get_utc_full_year
defs.docs: The getUTCFullYear() method returns the year in the specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: get_utc_hours
defs.docs: The getUTCHours() method returns the hours in the specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: get_utc_milliseconds
defs.docs:
The getUTCMilliseconds() method returns the milliseconds in the specified date according to
 universal time.

defs.name: get_utc_minutes
defs.docs: The getUTCMinutes() method returns the minutes in the specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: get_utc_month
defs.docs:
The getUTCMonth() returns the month of the specified date according to universal time, as a
 zero-based value (where zero indicates the first month of the year).

defs.name: get_utc_seconds
defs.docs: The getUTCSeconds() method returns the seconds in the specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_date
defs.docs: The setDate() method sets the day of the Date object relative to the beginning of the currently set month.

defs.name: set_full_year
defs.docs: The setFullYear() method sets the full year for a specified date according to local time. Returns new timestamp.

defs.name: set_hours
defs.docs:
The setHours() method sets the hours for a specified date according to local time, and returns the number of milliseconds
 since January 1, 1970 00:00:00 UTC until the time represented by the updated Date instance.

defs.name: set_milliseconds
defs.docs: The setMilliseconds() method sets the milliseconds for a specified date according to local time.

defs.name: set_minutes
defs.docs: The setMinutes() method sets the minutes for a specified date according to local time.

defs.name: set_month
defs.docs: The setMonth() method sets the month for a specified date according to the currently set year.

defs.name: set_seconds
defs.docs: The setSeconds() method sets the seconds for a specified date according to local time.

defs.name: set_time
defs.docs:
The setTime() method sets the Date object to the time represented by a number of milliseconds since
 January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC.

defs.name: set_utc_date
defs.docs: The setUTCDate() method sets the day of the month for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_utc_full_year
defs.docs: The setUTCFullYear() method sets the full year for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_utc_hours
defs.docs:
The setUTCHours() method sets the hour for a specified date according to universal time, and returns the number
 of milliseconds since  January 1, 1970 00:00:00 UTC until the time represented by the updated Date instance.

defs.name: set_utc_milliseconds
defs.docs: The setUTCMilliseconds() method sets the milliseconds for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_utc_minutes
defs.docs: The setUTCMinutes() method sets the minutes for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_utc_month
defs.docs: The setUTCMonth() method sets the month for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: set_utc_seconds
defs.docs: The setUTCSeconds() method sets the seconds for a specified date according to universal time.

defs.name: to_date_string
defs.docs: The toDateString() method returns the date portion of a Date object in human readable form in American English.

defs.name: to_iso_string
defs.docs:
The toISOString() method returns a string in simplified extended ISO format (ISO 8601), which is always 24 or 27
 characters long (YYYY-MM-DDTHH:mm:ss.sssZ or YYYYYY-MM-DDTHH:mm:ss.sssZ, respectively). The timezone is always zero
 UTC offset, as denoted by the suffix "Z".

defs.name: to_json
defs.docs: The toJSON() method returns a string representation of the Date object.

defs.name: to_string
defs.docs: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified Date object.

defs.name: to_time_string
defs.docs: The toTimeString() method returns the time portion of a Date object in human readable form in American English.

defs.name: to_utc_string
defs.docs: The toUTCString() method converts a date to a string, using the UTC time zone.

defs.name: value_of
defs.docs: The valueOf() method returns the primitive value of a Date object.

defs.name: Document
defs.docs:
The `Document` interface represents any web page loaded in the browser and
 serves as an entry point into the web page's content, which is the DOM tree.

defs.name: document
defs.docs: A global instance of [Document](struct.Document.html).

defs.name: create_document_fragment
defs.docs:
In an HTML document, the Document.createDocumentFragment() method creates a
 new empty DocumentFragment.

defs.name: create_element
defs.docs:
In an HTML document, the Document.createElement() method creates the HTML
 element specified by `tag`, or an HTMLUnknownElement if `tag` isn't
 recognized. In other documents, it creates an element with a null namespace URI.

defs.name: create_text_node
defs.docs: Creates a new text node.

defs.name: location
defs.docs:
Returns a [Location](struct.Location.html) object which contains
 information about the URL of the document and provides methods
 for changing that URL and loading another URL.

defs.name: body
defs.docs: Returns the `<body>` or `<frameset>` node of the current document, or null if no such element exists.

defs.name: head
defs.docs:
Returns the `<head>` element of the current document. If there are more than one `<head>`
 elements, the first one is returned.

defs.name: title
defs.docs: Gets the title of the document.

defs.name: set_title
defs.docs: Sets the title of the document.

defs.name: document_element
defs.docs:
Returns the Element that is the root element of the document (for example, the `<html>`
 element for HTML documents).

defs.name: RequestAnimationFrameHandle
defs.docs: A handle to a pending animation frame request.

defs.name: cancel
defs.docs: Cancels an animation frame request.

defs.name: Window
defs.docs: The `Window` object represents a window containing a DOM document.

defs.name: window
defs.docs: A global instance of [Window](struct.Window.html).

defs.name: alert
defs.docs:
The Window.alert() method displays an alert dialog
 with the optional specified content and an OK button.

defs.name: local_storage
defs.docs:
The `local_storage` property allows you to access a local [Storage](struct.Storage.html)
 object.

defs.name: session_storage
defs.docs:
The `session_storage` property allows you to access a session [Storage](struct.Storage.html)
 object for the current origin.

defs.name: location
defs.docs:
Returns a [Location](struct.Location.html) object which contains
 information about the URL of the document and provides methods
 for changing that URL and loading another URL.

defs.name: request_animation_frame
defs.docs:
You should call this method whenever you're ready to update your animation onscreen.
 This will request that your animation function be called before the browser performs the next repaint.
 The number of callbacks is usually 60 times per second, but will generally match the display refresh
 rate in most web browsers as per W3C recommendation. request_animation_frame() calls are paused in most browsers
 when running in background tabs or hidden iframes in order to improve performance and battery life.

defs.name: history
defs.docs:
Returns the global [History](struct.History.html) object, which provides methods to
 manipulate the browser history.

defs.name: inner_width
defs.docs:
Returns the width (in pixels) of the browser window viewport including, if rendered,
 the vertical scrollbar.

defs.name: inner_height
defs.docs:
Returns the height (in pixels) of the browser window viewport including, if rendered,
 the horizontal scrollbar.

defs.name: outer_width
defs.docs:
Returns the width of the outside of the browser window. It represents the width
 of the whole browser window including sidebar (if expanded), window chrome
 and window resizing borders/handles.

defs.name: outer_height
defs.docs:
Returns the height of the outside of the browser window. It represents the height
 of the whole browser window including sidebar (if expanded), window chrome
 and window resizing borders/handles.

defs.name: page_y_offset
defs.docs:
The read-only Window property pageYOffset is an alias for scrollY; as such, it returns
 the number of pixels the document is currently scrolled along the vertical axis (that is,
 up or down), with a value of 0.0 indicating that the top edge of the Document is currently
 aligned with the top edge of the window's content area.

defs.name: page_x_offset
defs.docs: This is an alias for scrollX.

defs.name: IEvent
defs.docs:
The `IEvent` interface represents any event which takes place in the DOM; some
 are user-generated (such as mouse or keyboard events), while others are
 generated by APIs (such as events that indicate an animation has finished
 running, a video has been paused, and so forth). There are many types of event,
 some of which useother interfaces based on the main `IEvent` interface. `IEvent`
 itself contains the properties and methods which are common to all events.

defs.name: bubbles
defs.docs: Indicates whether this event bubbles upward through the DOM.

defs.name: cancel_bubble
defs.docs: A historical alias to `Event.stopPropagation()`.

defs.name: set_cancel_bubble
defs.docs:
A historical alias to `Event.stopPropagation()`.
 Setting this to `true` before returning from an event handler will stop propagation
 of the event.

defs.name: cancelable
defs.docs: Indicates whether the event is cancelable.

defs.name: current_target
defs.docs: A reference to the currently registered target of this event.

defs.name: default_prevented
defs.docs: Indicates whether `preventDefault` has been called on this event.

defs.name: event_phase
defs.docs: Indicates which phase of event flow is currently being evaluated.

defs.name: stop_immediate_propagation
defs.docs: Prevents any further listeners from being called for this event.

defs.name: stop_propagation
defs.docs: Stops the propagation of this event to descendants in the DOM.

defs.name: target
defs.docs: Returns a reference to the target to which this event was originally registered.

defs.name: time_stamp
defs.docs: Returns the time in milliseconds at which this event was created.

defs.name: is_trusted
defs.docs: Indicates whether the event was generated by a user action.

defs.name: event_type
defs.docs:
Returnsa string containing the type of event. It is set when
 the event is constructed and is the name commonly used to refer
 to the specific event.

defs.name: prevent_default
defs.docs:
Cancels the event if it is cancelable, without
 stopping further propagation of the event.

defs.name: None
defs.docs: No event is currently being processed.

defs.name: Capturing
defs.docs: The event is being propagated down through the target's ancestors.

defs.name: AtTarget
defs.docs: The target is currently processing the event.

defs.name: Bubbling
defs.docs: The event is propagating back up through the target's ancestors.

defs.name: EventPhase
defs.docs: Indicates the phase of event flow during event proessing.

defs.name: ConcreteEvent
defs.docs: A trait representing a concrete event type.

defs.name: EVENT_TYPE
defs.docs: A string representing the event type.

defs.name: Event
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IEvent](trait.IEvent.html)
 interface.

defs.name: IUiEvent
defs.docs: The `IUiEvent` interface represents simple user interface events.

defs.name: detail
defs.docs: Provides the current click count for this event, if applicable.

defs.name: view
defs.docs: Returns the `WindowProxy` that generated the event.

defs.name: UiEvent
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IUiEvent](trait.IUiEvent.html)
 interface.

defs.name: EventListenerHandle
defs.docs: A handle to a particular event listener.

defs.name: remove
defs.docs:
Removes the listener from the [IEventTarget](trait.IEventTarget.html) on
 which it was previously registered.

defs.name: IEventTarget
defs.docs:
`IEventTarget` is an interface implemented by objects that
 can receive events and may have listeners for them.

defs.name: add_event_listener
defs.docs:
Adds given event handler to the list of event listeners for
 the specified `EventTarget` on which it's called.

defs.name: dispatch_event
defs.docs:
Dispatches an `Event` at this `EventTarget`, invoking the affected event listeners in the
 appropriate order.

defs.name: EventTarget
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IEventTarget](trait.IEventTarget.html)
 interface.

defs.name: Shallow
defs.docs: Will not clone the children.

defs.name: Deep
defs.docs: Will clone the children.

defs.name: CloneKind
defs.docs: An enum which determines whenever the DOM [Node](trait.INode.html)'s children will also be cloned or not.

defs.name: INode
defs.docs: `INode` is an interface from which a number of DOM API object types inherit.

defs.name: as_node
defs.docs: Casts a reference to this object into a reference to a [Node](struct.Node.html).

defs.name: append_child
defs.docs: Adds a node to the end of the list of children of a specified parent node.

defs.name: remove_child
defs.docs: Removes a child node from the DOM.

defs.name: clone_node
defs.docs: Returns a duplicate of the node on which this method was called.

defs.name: contains
defs.docs: Checks whenever a given node is a descendant of this one or not.

defs.name: insert_before
defs.value: fn <T, U> (&self, new_node: &T, reference_node: &U) -> Result<Node, InsertNodeError>
defs.docs: Inserts the specified node before the reference node as a child of the current node.

defs.name: replace_child
defs.value: fn <T, U> (&self, new_child: &T, old_child: &U) -> Result<Node, InsertNodeError>
defs.docs: Replaces one hild node of the specified nodewith another.

defs.name: parent_node
defs.docs: Returns the parent of this node in the DOM tree.

defs.name: first_child
defs.docs: Returns the node's first child in the tree, or `None` if the node is childless.

defs.name: last_child
defs.docs: Returns the node's last child in the tree, or `None` if the node is childless.

defs.name: next_sibling
defs.docs: Returns the node's next sibling in the tree, or `None` if there isn't such a node.

defs.name: node_name
defs.docs: Returns the name of the node.

defs.name: node_type
defs.docs: Returns the type of the node.

defs.name: node_value
defs.docs: Returns the value of the node.

defs.name: set_node_value
defs.docs: Sets the value of the node.

defs.name: owner_document
defs.docs: Returns the `Document` that this node belongs to.

defs.name: parent_element
defs.docs:
Returns an `Element` that is the parent of this node. Returns `null` if the node
 has no parent or the parent is not an `Element`.

defs.name: previous_sibling
defs.docs: Returns the node's previous sibling in the tree, or `None` if there isn't such a node.

defs.name: text_content
defs.docs: A property which represents the text content of a node and its descendants.

defs.name: set_text_content
defs.docs:
Sets the text content of this node; calling thil removes all
 of node's children and replaces them with a single text node
 with the given value.

defs.name: child_nodes
defs.docs: Returns a live collection of child nodes of this node.

defs.name: base_uri
defs.docs: Gets the base URL.

defs.name: has_child_nodes
defs.docs: Returns whether this node has children nodes.

defs.name: is_default_namespace
defs.docs: Determines whether the given namespace is the default namespace of this node.

defs.name: is_equal_node
defs.docs:
Tests whether this node is equal to another node. Two nodes are equal if
 they have the same type, defining characteristics, matching attributes,
 and so on.

defs.name: is_same_node

The HTML `<canvas>` element provides an empty graphic zone on which specific JavaScript APIs

 interpreted in CSS pixels. When the attribute is not specified, or if it is set to an
 invalid value, like a negative, the default value of 300 is used.

defs.docs:

 interpreted in CSS pixels. When the attribute is not specified, or if it is set to an
 invalid value, like a negative, the default value of 300 is used.

defs.name: Location

The `Location` interface represents the location (URL) of the object it
 is linked to. Changes done on it are reflected on the object it relates
 to. Both the [Document](struct.Document.html) and [Window](struct.Window.html)
 interface have such a linked `Location`, accessible via [Document::location](struct.Document.html#method.location)
 and [Window::location](struct.Window.html#method.location) respectively.

defs.name: href

defs.name: origin
defs.docs:
Returns a `String` containing the Unicode serialization of the origin of the represented
 URL, that is:

defs.name: protocol

defs.name: host
defs.docs:
Returns a `String` containing the host (i.e. hostname) and then, if the port of the
 URL is nonempty, a ':', and the port of the URL.

defs.name: hostname
defs.docs: Returns a `String` which is the domain of the URL

defs.name: port
defs.docs: Returns a `String` containing the port number or `""` if there is no port.

defs.docs: Returns a `String` containing an initial '/' followed by the path of the URL.

defs.docs:
Returns a `String` which is a search string, also called a query string, that is a `String`
 containing a '?' followed by the parameters of the URL.

defs.name: hash
defs.docs:
Returns a `String` containing a '#' followed by the fragment
 identifier of the URL. The fragment is not percent-decoded.

defs.name: FileList
len

The FileReader object lets web applications asynchronously read the contents of files
 (or raw data buffers) stored on the user's computer, using [File](struct.File.html)
 or [Blob](struct.Blob.html) objects to specify the file or data to read.

defs.name: String
defs.docs: A string; a result of calling [FileReader::read_as_text](struct.FileReader.html#method.read_as_text).

defs.name: ArrayBuffer
defs.docs: An [ArrayBuffer](struct.ArrayBuffer.html); a result of calling [FileReader::read_as_array_buffer](struct.FileReader.html#method.read_as_array_buffer).

defs.name: FileReaderResult
defs.docs: The [result](struct.FileReader.html#method.result) of a read operation performed with a [FileReader](struct.File.html).

defs.docs: A number indicating the state of the `FileReader`.

defs.docs: Returns a newly constructed `FileReader`.

defs.docs:

 the `result` attribute will contain the contents of the file as a text string.

defs.docs:
Starts reading the contents of the specified blob. Once finished
 the `result` attribute will contain the contents of the file as an [TypedArray](struct.ArrayBuffer.html).

 is complete, and the format of the data depends on which of the methods was used
 to initiate the read operation.

defs.name: XmlHttpRequest
defs.docs:
Use XmlHttpRequest (XHR) objects to interact with servers.
 You can retrieve data from a URL without having to do a full page refresh.
 This enables a Web page to update just part of a page without disrupting
 what the user is doing. XmlHttpRequest is used heavily in Ajax programming.

defs.name: Unsent
defs.docs: Client has been created. [open()](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.open) not called yet.

defs.name: Opened
defs.docs: [open()](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.open) has been called.

defs.name: HeadersReceived
defs.docs: [send()](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.send) has been called, and headers and [status()](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.status) are available.

defs.name: Loading
defs.docs: Downloading; [reponse_text()](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.reponse_text) holds partial data.

defs.name: Done
defs.docs: The operation is complete.

defs.name: XhrReadyState
defs.docs: An enum indicating the state of the `XmlHttpRequest`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates new `XmlHttpRequest`.

defs.name: ready_state
defs.docs: Returns the current state of the request as a [XhrReadyState](enum.XhrReadyState.html).

defs.name: response_text
defs.docs:
Returns a string that contains the response to the request as text, or None
 if the request was unsuccessful or has not yet been sent.

defs.name: status
defs.docs: Returns an unsigned short with the status of the response of the request.

defs.name: open
defs.docs: Open connection with given method (ie GET or POST), and the url to hit.

defs.name: get_response_header
defs.docs:
Returns the string containing the text of the specified header. If there
 are multiple response headers with the same name, then their values are
 returned as a single concatenated string.

defs.name: set_request_header
defs.docs:
Sets the value of an HTTP request header. Must be called after `open()`,
 but before `send()`. If this method is called several times with the same
 header, the values are merged into one single request header.

defs.name: send
defs.docs: Send request on an open connection with no data

defs.name: send_with_string
defs.docs: Send request on an open connection with string body

defs.name: send_with_bytes
defs.docs: Send request on an open connection with a byte array body

defs.name: abort
defs.docs:
Aborts the request if it has already been sent.
 When a request is aborted, its [ready_state](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.ready_state) is changed to [Done](enum.XhrReadyState.html#variant.Done)
 and the [status](struct.XmlHttpRequest.html#method.status) code is set to
 [Unsent](enum.XhrReadyState.html#variant.Unsent).

defs.name: SourceOver
defs.docs: Draws new shapes over existing canvas content

defs.name: SourceIn
defs.docs: Draws new shapes over existing canvas content, but only where existing canvas content overlaps. Anything not in that area becomes transparent.

defs.name: SourceOut
defs.docs: New shapes are drawn where there is no existing canvas content. Everything else (including old canvas content) is made transparent.

defs.name: SourceAtop
defs.docs: Draws new shapes only where there is existing canvas content, over existing canvas content

defs.name: DestinationOver
defs.docs: Draws new shapes behind existing canvas content

defs.name: DestinationIn
defs.docs: Keeps existing canvas content where it overlaps with the new shape. Everything outside the overlap is made transparent.

defs.name: DestinationOut
defs.docs: The existing content is kept where it doesn't overlap with the new shape. Everything else, including the new shape area, is made transparent.

defs.name: DestinationAtop
defs.docs: Existing content is kept only where it overlaps with the new shape. The new shape is drawn behind the existing content.

defs.name: Lighter
defs.docs: Where both shapes overlap, the new color is determined by adding color values

defs.name: Copy
defs.docs: Only the new shape is shown

defs.name: Xor
defs.docs: Where both shapes overlap, make it transparent

defs.name: Multiply
defs.docs: The pixels of the new and old layer are multiplied. (Pixel values are in the range of [0,1], so this makes a darker picture)

defs.name: Screen
defs.docs: Pixels from both new and old are inverted, multiplied together, then inverted again. (Pixel values are in the range of [0,1], so this makes a lighter picture)

defs.name: Overlay
defs.docs: Applies Multiply to dark colors in the existing content, and Screen to bright colors in the existing content

defs.name: Darken
defs.docs: Retains the darkest pixels

defs.name: Lighten
defs.docs: Retains the lighest pixels

defs.name: ColorDodge
defs.docs: Divides the bottom layer by the inverted top layer.

defs.name: ColorBurn
defs.docs: Divides the inverted bottom layer by the top layer, and then inverts the result.

defs.name: HardLight
defs.docs: A combination of multiply and screen like overlay, but with top and bottom layer swapped.

defs.name: SoftLight
defs.docs: A softer version of hard-light. Pure black or white does not result in pure black or white.

defs.name: Difference
defs.docs: Subtracts the bottom layer from the top layer or the other way round to always get a positive value.

defs.name: Exclusion
defs.docs: Like difference, but with lower contrast.

defs.name: Hue
defs.docs: Preserves the luma and chroma of the bottom layer, while adopting the hue of the top layer.

defs.name: Saturation
defs.docs: Preserves the luma and hue of the bottom layer, while adopting the chroma of the top layer.

defs.name: Color
defs.docs: Preserves the luma of the bottom layer, while adopting the hue and chroma of the top layer.

defs.name: Luminosity
defs.docs: Preserves the hue and chroma of the bottom layer, while adopting the luma of the top layer.

defs.name: arc_to
defs.value: fn (&self, x1: f64, y1: f64, x2: f64, y2: f64, radius: f64) -> Result<(), IndexSizeError>
defs.docs:
Adds an arc to the path with the given control points and radius.
 The arc drawn will be a part of a circle, never elliptical. 
 Typical use could be making a rounded corner.
 One way to think about the arc drawn is to imagine two straight segments, from the 
 starting point (latest point in current path) to the first control point, and then 
 from the first control point to the second control point. These two segments form 
 a sharp corner with the first control point being in the corner. Using arcTo, the 
 corner will instead be an arc with the given radius.
 The arc is tangential to both segments, which can sometimes produce surprising results, 
 e.g. if the radius given is larger than the distance between the starting point and the first control point.
 If the radius specified doesn't make the arc meet the starting point (latest point in the current path), 
 the starting point is connected to the arc with a straight line segment.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/arcTo)

defs.name: bezier_curve_to
defs.value: fn (&self, cp1x: f64, cp1y: f64, cp2x: f64, cp2y: f64, x: f64, y: f64) -> ()
defs.docs:
Adds a cubic Bzier curve to the path. It requires three points. The first two points 
 are control points and the third one is the end point. The starting point is the last 
 point in the current path, which can be changed using moveTo() before creating the Bzier curve.

defs.docs:
Creates a gradient along the line given by the coordinates represented by the parameters.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/createLinearGradient)

defs.name: create_image_data
defs.value: fn (&self, width: f64, height: f64) -> Result<ImageData, IndexSizeError>
defs.docs:
Creates a new, blank ImageData object with the specified dimensions. 
 All of the pixels in the new object are transparent black.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/createImageData)

defs.name: create_image_data_size_of
defs.docs:
Creates a new, blank ImageData object with the specified dimensions. 
 All of the pixels in the new object are transparent black.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/createImageData)

defs.name: create_pattern_image
defs.value: fn (&self, image: ImageElement, repetition: Repetition) -> CanvasPattern
defs.docs:
Creates a pattern using the specified image (a CanvasImageSource). It repeats the source in 
 the directions specified by the repetition argument. This method returns a CanvasPattern.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/createPattern)

defs.name: create_radial_gradient
defs.value: fn (&self, x0: f64, y0: f64, r0: f64, x1: f64, y1: f64, r1: f64) -> Result<CanvasGradient, IndexSizeError>
defs.docs:
Creates a radial gradient given by the coordinates of the two circles represented by the parameters. 
 This method returns a CanvasGradient.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/createRadialGradient)

defs.name: draw_focus_if_needed
defs.docs:
Draws a focus ring around the current path or given path, If a given element is focused.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/drawFocusIfNeeded)

defs.name: draw_image
defs.value: fn (&self, image: ImageElement, dx: f64, dy: f64) -> Result<(), DrawImageError>
defs.docs:
Provides different ways to draw an image onto the canvas.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/drawImage)

defs.name: draw_image_d
defs.value: fn (&self, image: ImageElement, dx: f64, dy: f64, d_width: f64, d_height: f64) -> Result<(), DrawImageError>
defs.docs:
Provides different ways to draw an image onto the canvas.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/drawImage)

defs.name: draw_image_s
defs.value: fn (&self, image: ImageElement, sx: f64, sy: f64, s_width: f64, s_height: f64, dx: f64, dy: f64, d_width: f64, d_height: f64) -> Result<(), DrawImageError>
defs.docs:
Provides different ways to draw an image onto the canvas.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/drawImage)

defs.name: fill
defs.docs:
Fills the current or given path with the current fill style using the non-zero or even-odd winding rule.
 
 ctx.fill(path, fillRule) is not supported because [(Path2D)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Path2D) is still experimental
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/fill)

defs.name: fill_rect
defs.value: fn (&self, x: f64, y: f64, width: f64, height: f64) -> ()
defs.docs:
Draws a filled rectangle whose starting point is at the coordinates (x, y) with the
 specified width and height and whose style is determined by the fillStyle attribute.

defs.name: fill_text
defs.value: fn (&self, text: &str, x: f64, y: f64, max_width: Option<f64>) -> ()
defs.docs:
Draws a text string at the specified coordinates, filling the string's characters
 with the current foreground color. An optional parameter allows specifying a maximum
 width for the rendered text, which the user agent will achieve by condensing the
 text or by using a lower font size.

defs.name: get_image_data
defs.value: fn (&self, sx: f64, sy: f64, sw: f64, sh: f64) -> Result<ImageData, GetImageDataError>
defs.docs:
Returns an ImageData object representing the underlying pixel data for the area of the 
 canvas denoted by the rectangle which starts at (sx, sy) and has an sw width and sh height. 
 This method is not affected by the canvas transformation matrix.
 Pixels outside of the canvas area are present as transparent black values in the returned ImageData.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/getImageData)

defs.name: get_line_dash
defs.docs:
Gets the current line dash pattern.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/getLineDash)

defs.name: is_point_in_path
defs.value: fn (&self, x: f64, y: f64, fill_rule: FillRule) -> bool
defs.docs:
Reports whether or not the specified point is contained in the current path.
 
 ctx.isPointInPath(path, x, y) and ctx.isPointInPath(path, x, y, fillRule) 
 are not supported because [(Path2D)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Path2D) is still experimental 
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/isPointInPath)

defs.name: is_point_in_stroke
defs.value: fn (&self, x: f64, y: f64) -> bool
defs.docs:
Reports whether or not the specified point is inside the area contained by the stroking of a path.
 
 ctx.isPointInStroke(path, x, y) is not supported because [(Path2D)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Path2D) is still experimental 
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/isPointInStroke)

defs.name: line_to
defs.docs:
Connects the last point in the sub-path to the x, y coordinates with a straight line (but does not actually draw it).
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/lineTo)

defs.name: measure_text
defs.docs:
Returns a TextMetrics object that contains information about the measured text (such as its width for example).
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/measureText)

defs.name: move_to
defs.docs:
Moves the starting point of a new sub-path to the (x, y) coordinates.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/moveTo)

defs.name: put_image_data
defs.value: fn (&self, image_data: ImageData, dx: f32, dy: f32) -> Result<(), InvalidStateError>
defs.docs:
Paints data from the given ImageData object onto the bitmap. If a dirty rectangle is provided, only the pixels 
 from that rectangle are painted. This method is not affected by the canvas transformation matrix.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/putImageData)

defs.name: put_image_data_dirty
defs.value: fn (&self, image_data: ImageData, dx: f32, dy: f32, dirty_x: f32, dirty_y: f32, dirty_width: f32, dirty_height: f32) -> Result<(), InvalidStateError>
defs.docs:
Paints data from the given ImageData object onto the bitmap. If a dirty rectangle is provided, only the pixels 
 from that rectangle are painted. This method is not affected by the canvas transformation matrix.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/putImageData)

defs.name: quadratic_curve_to
defs.value: fn (&self, cpx: f64, cpy: f64, x: f64, y: f64) -> ()
defs.docs:
Adds a quadratic Bzier curve to the path. It requires two points. 
 The first point is a control point and the second one is the end point. 
 The starting point is the last point in the current path, which can be changed using 
 moveTo() before creating the quadratic Bzier curve.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/quadraticCurveTo)

defs.name: rect
defs.value: fn (&self, x: f64, y: f64, width: f64, height: f64) -> ()
defs.docs:
Creates a path for a rectangle at position (x, y) with a size that is determined by width and height. 
 Those four points are connected by straight lines and the sub-path is marked as closed, 
 so that you can fill or stroke this rectangle.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/rect)

defs.name: restore
defs.docs:
Restores the most recently saved canvas state by popping the top entry in the drawing state stack. 
 If there is no saved state, this method does nothing.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/restore)

defs.name: rotate
defs.docs:
Adds a rotation to the transformation matrix. The angle argument represents a clockwise rotation angle and is expressed in radians.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/rotate)

defs.name: save
defs.docs:
Saves the entire state of the canvas by pushing the current state onto a stack.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/save)

defs.name: scale
defs.docs:
adds a scaling transformation to the canvas units by x horizontally and by y vertically.
 By default, one unit on the canvas is exactly one pixel. If we apply, for instance, a scaling factor of 0.5, 
 the resulting unit would become 0.5 pixels and so shapes would be drawn at half size. 
 In a similar way setting the scaling factor to 2.0 would increase the unit size and one unit now becomes two pixels. 
 This results in shapes being drawn twice as large.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/scale)

defs.name: set_line_dash
defs.docs:
Sets the line dash pattern used when stroking lines, using an array of values which specify alternating lengths of lines and gaps which describe the pattern.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/setLineDash)

defs.name: set_transform
defs.docs:
Resets (overrides) the current transformation to the identity matrix and then invokes a transformation described by the arguments of this method.
 See also the transform() method, which does not override the current transform matrix and multiplies it with a given one.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/setTransform)

defs.name: stroke
defs.docs:
Strokes the current or given path with the current stroke style using the non-zero winding rule.
 
 ctx.stroke(path) is not supported because [(Path2D)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Path2D) is still experimental
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/stroke)

defs.name: stroke_rect
defs.value: fn (&self, x: f64, y: f64, width: f64, height: f64) -> ()
defs.docs:
Paints a rectangle which has a starting point at (x, y) and has a w width and an h height onto the canvas, using the current stroke style.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/strokeRect)

defs.name: stroke_text
defs.value: fn (&self, text: &str, x: f64, y: f64, max_width: Option<f64>) -> ()
defs.docs:
Strokes  that is, draws the outlines of  the characters of a specified text string at the given (x, y) position. 
 If the optional fourth parameter for a maximum width is provided, the text is scaled to fit that width.
 See the CanvasRenderingContext2D.fillText() method to draw the text with the characters filled with color rather than having just their outlines drawn.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/strokeText)

defs.name: transform
defs.docs:
Multiplies the current transformation with the matrix described by the arguments of this method. 
 You are able to scale, rotate, move and skew the context.
 See also the setTransform() method which resets the current transform to the identity matrix and then invokes transform().
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/transform)

defs.name: translate
defs.docs:
Adds a translation transformation by moving the canvas and its origin x horizontally and y vertically on the grid.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/translate)

defs.name: get_width
defs.docs:
Contains the text's advance width (the width of that inline box) in CSS pixels.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/TextMetrics/width)

defs.name: MutationObserver
defs.docs: Provides a way to receive notifications about changes to the DOM.

defs.name: MutationObserverInit
defs.value: MutationObserverInit { child_list, attributes, character_data, subtree, attribute_old_value, character_data_old_value, attribute_filter }
defs.docs: Specifies which changes should be observed for the target.

defs.name: child_list
defs.docs: If `true` it will observe all inserts and removals of the target's children (including text nodes).

defs.name: attributes
defs.docs: If `true` it will observe all changes to the target's attributes.

defs.name: character_data
defs.docs: If `true` it will observe all changes to the `CharacterData`'s data.

defs.name: subtree
defs.docs: If `true` it will observe all changes to the target, the target's children, and the target's sub-children.

defs.name: attribute_old_value
defs.docs: If `true` it will store the target's old attribute value in [`old_value`](enum.MutationRecord.html#variant.Attribute.field.old_value).

defs.name: character_data_old_value
defs.docs: If `true` it will store the `CharacterData`'s old data in [`old_data`](enum.MutationRecord.html#variant.CharacterData.field.old_data).

defs.name: attribute_filter
defs.docs: If `Some` it will only observe the specified attributes. The attributes should be specified without a namespace.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Returns a new [`MutationObserverHandle`](struct.MutationObserverHandle.html) with the given callback.

defs.name: observe
defs.value: fn <T> (&self, target: &T, options: MutationObserverInit) -> Result<(), TODO>
defs.docs: Starts observing changes to the `target`.

defs.name: disconnect
defs.docs: Stops observing all targets.

defs.name: take_records
defs.docs: Empties the `MutationObserver`'s record queue and returns what was in there.

defs.name: MutationObserverHandle
defs.docs: A wrapper which ensures that memory is properly cleaned up when it's no longer needed.

defs.name: Attribute
defs.docs: One of the target's attributes was changed.

defs.name: CharacterData
defs.docs: The target's data was changed.

defs.name: ChildList
defs.value: MutationRecord::ChildList { target, inserted_nodes, removed_nodes, previous_sibling, next_sibling }
defs.docs: The children of the target were changed.

defs.name: MutationRecord
defs.docs: Contains information about an individual change to the DOM.

defs.name: IError
defs.docs:
Represents the JavaScript `Error` interface. An `Error` is thrown whenever a run-time error
 occurs.

defs.name: message
defs.docs: Returns a human-readable description of the error.

defs.name: name
defs.docs: Returns a name specifiying the type of error.

defs.name: Error
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript `Error` object. An `Error` is thrown whenever a run-time error
 occurs.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates a new `Error` with the specified `description`.

defs.name: IDomException
defs.docs:
The `IDomException` interface represents an abnormal event which occurs as the result of
 calling a web API.

defs.name: DomException
defs.docs: A reference to a JavaScript `DOMException` object.

defs.name: HierarchyRequestError
defs.docs: Occurs when an operation would result in an incorrect node tree.

defs.name: InvalidAccessError
defs.docs: Occurs when an object does not support an operation or argument.

defs.name: NotFoundError
defs.docs: Occurs when the specified object cannot be found.

defs.name: SecurityError
defs.docs: Occurs when the requested operation is insecure.

defs.name: SyntaxError
defs.docs: Occurs when an argument does not match the expected pattern.

defs.name: IndexSizeError
defs.docs: Occurs when an argument is out of range.

defs.name: InvalidStateError
defs.docs: Occurs when an object is in an invalid state.

defs.name: TypeError
defs.docs: Used to indicate an unsuccessful operation when none of the other NativeError objects are an appropriate indication of the failure cause.

defs.name: NotSupportedError
defs.docs: Used to indicate an unsuccessful operation when none of the other NativeError objects are an appropriate indication of the failure cause.

defs.name: InvalidCharacterError
defs.docs: Used to indicate the string contains one or more characters which are invalid.

defs.name: InvalidPointerId
defs.docs: Used to indicate that a pointer id passed as an argument was for some reason invalid.

defs.name: ChangeEvent
defs.docs:
The `ChangeEvent` is fired for input, select, and textarea
 elements when a change to the element's value is committed
 by the user. Unlike the input event, the change event is not
 necessarily fired for each change to an element's value.

defs.name: InputEvent
defs.docs:
The `InputEvent` is fired synchronously when the value of an
 input, select, or textarea element is changed. For input elements
 with type=checkbox or type=radio, the input event should fire when
 a user toggles the control (via touch, mouse or keyboard) per the
 HTML5 specification, but historically, this has not been the case.
 Check compatibility, or attach to the change event instead for
 elements of these types.

defs.name: ResourceLoadEvent
defs.docs: The `ResourceLoadEvent` is fired when a resource and its dependent resources have finished loading.

defs.name: ResourceAbortEvent
defs.docs: The `ResourceAbortEvent` is fired when the loading of a resource has been aborted.

defs.name: ResourceErrorEvent
defs.docs:
The `ResourceErrorEvent` is fired when an error occurred; the exact circumstances vary,
 since this event is used from a variety of APIs.

defs.name: ResizeEvent
defs.docs: The resize event is fired when the document view has been resized.

defs.name: ReadyStateChangeEvent
defs.docs: The readystatechange event is fired when the readyState attribute of a document has changed.

defs.name: SubmitEvent
defs.docs: The submit event is fired when a form is submitted.

defs.name: IFocusEvent
defs.docs:
The `IFocusEvent` interface represents focus-related
 events.

defs.name: related_target
defs.docs: Returns the secondary target of this event, if any.

defs.name: FocusRelatedEvent
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IFocusEvent](trait.IFocusEvent.html)
 interface.

defs.name: FocusEvent
defs.docs:
The `FocusEvent` is fired when an element has received focus. The main
 difference between this event and focusin is that only the latter bubbles.

defs.name: BlurEvent
defs.docs:
The `BlurEvent` is fired when an element has lost focus. The main difference
 between this event and focusout is that only the latter bubbles.

defs.name: HashChangeEvent
defs.docs:
The `HashChangeEvent` is fired when the fragment
 identifier of the URL has changed (the part of the URL
 that follows the # symbol, including the # symbol).

defs.name: old_url
defs.docs: The previous URL from which the window was navigated.

defs.name: new_url
defs.docs: The new URL to which the window was navigated.

defs.name: PopStateEvent
defs.docs:
A `PopStateEvent` is dispatched to the window every time the active history entry changes
 between two history entries for the same document. If the history entry being activated was
 created by a call to `history.push_state()` or was affected by a call to
 `history.replace_state()`, the `PopStateEvent`'s state property contains a copy of the history
 entry's state object.

defs.name: state
defs.docs:
The state object associated to the new history entry, if that entry was created with
 push_state or affected by replace_state.

defs.name: IKeyboardEvent
defs.docs:
`IKeyboardEvent` objects describe a user interaction with the
 keyboard. Each event describes a key; the event type identifies
 what kind of activity was performed.

defs.name: alt_key
defs.docs: Indicates whether the Alt key was down when this event was fired.

defs.name: code
defs.docs: Returns a code value that indicates the physical key pressed on the keyboard.

defs.name: ctrl_key
defs.docs: Returns whether the Ctrl key was down when this event was fired.

defs.name: get_modifier_state
defs.docs: Returns whether a modifier key was down when this event was fired.

defs.name: is_composing
defs.docs: Returns whether this event was fired during composition.

defs.name: location
defs.docs: Returns the location of the key on the keyboard.

defs.name: key
defs.docs: Returns the value of a key or keys pressed by the user.

defs.name: meta_key
defs.docs: Indicates whether the Meta key was down when this event was fired.

defs.name: repeat
defs.docs: Indicates whether the key is held down such that it is repeating.

defs.name: shift_key
defs.docs: Indicates whether the Shift key was down when this event was fired.

defs.name: ModifierKey
defs.value: ModifierKey::{Alt, AltGr, CapsLock, Ctrl, Function, FunctionLock, Hyper, Meta, NumLock, OS, ScrollLock, Shift, Super, Symbol, SymbolLock}
defs.docs: A modifier key on the keyboard.

defs.name: Standard
defs.docs: The key has only one version, or the location can't be distinguished.

defs.name: Left
defs.docs: The left-hand version of a key.

defs.name: Right
defs.docs: The right-hand version of a key.

defs.name: Numpad
defs.docs: The key was on a numeric pad.

defs.name: Mobile
defs.docs: The key was on a mobile device.

defs.name: Joystick
defs.docs: The key was on a joystick.

defs.name: KeyboardLocation
defs.value: KeyboardLocation::{Standard, Left, Right, Numpad, Mobile, Joystick}
defs.docs: The location on the keyboard of a key.

defs.name: KeyboardEvent
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IKeyboardEvent](trait.IKeyboardEvent.html)
 interface.

defs.name: KeyPressEvent
defs.docs:
The `KeyPressEvent` is fired when a key is pressed down. It's only
 fired for keys which produce a character value.

defs.name: KeyDownEvent
defs.docs:
The `KeyDownEvent` is fired when a key is pressed down.
 Unlike the `KeyPressEvent` event it's also fired for keys which
 do not produce a character value.

defs.name: KeyUpEvent
defs.docs: The `KeyUpEvent` is fired when a key is released.

defs.name: IMouseEvent
defs.docs:
The `IMouseEvent` interface represents events that occur due to the user
 interacting with a pointing device (such as a mouse).

defs.name: alt_key
defs.docs: Returns whether the Alt key was down when this event was fired.

defs.name: button
defs.docs: Indicates the mouse button that fired this event.

defs.name: buttons
defs.docs: Indicates which mouse buttons were down when this event was fired.

defs.name: client_x
defs.docs: Returns the X position in the application's client area where this event occured.

defs.name: client_y
defs.docs: Returns the Y position in the application's client area where this event occured.

defs.name: offset_x
defs.docs: Returns the X position on the target element where this event occured.

defs.name: offset_y
defs.docs: Returns the Y position on the target element where this event occured.

defs.name: ctrl_key
defs.docs: Indicates whether the Ctrl key was down when this event fired.

defs.name: get_modifier_state
defs.docs: Returns the current state of the specified modifier key.

defs.name: meta_key
defs.docs: Indicates whether the Meta key was down when this event fired.

defs.name: movement_x
defs.docs:
Returns the change in X coordinate of the pointer between this event and the previous
 MouseMove event.

defs.name: movement_y
defs.docs:
Returns the change in Y coordinate of the pointer between this event and the previous
 MouseMove event.

defs.name: region
defs.docs: Returns the ID of the hit region affected by the event.

defs.name: related_target
defs.docs: Returns the secondary target of this event, if any.

defs.name: screen_x
defs.docs: Returns the X position of the pointer in screen coordinates.

defs.name: screen_y
defs.docs: Returns the Y position of the pointer in screen coordinates.

defs.name: shift_key
defs.docs: Indicates whether the Shift key was down when this event was fired.

defs.name: Left
defs.docs: The left mouse button.

defs.name: Wheel
defs.docs: The mouse wheel/middle mouse button.

defs.name: Right
defs.docs: The right mouse button.

defs.name: Button4
defs.docs: The fourth mouse button (browser back).

defs.name: Button5
defs.docs: The fifth mouse button (browser forward).

defs.name: MouseButton
defs.docs: Represents buttons on a mouse during mouse events.

defs.name: MouseButtonsState
defs.docs: Represents the state of mouse buttons in a `MouseEvent`.

defs.name: MouseEvent
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IMouseEvent](trait.IMouseEvent.html)
 interface.

defs.name: ClickEvent
defs.docs:
The `ClickEvent` is fired when a pointing device button (usually a
 mouse's primary button) is pressed and released on a single element.

defs.name: DoubleClickEvent
defs.docs:
The `DoubleClickEvent` is fired when a pointing device button
 (usually a mouse's primary button) is clicked twice on a single
 element.

defs.name: MouseDownEvent
defs.docs:
The `MouseDownEvent` is fired when a pointing device button is pressed on
 an element.

defs.name: MouseUpEvent
defs.docs:
The `MouseUpEvent` is fired when a pointing device button is released
 over an element.

defs.name: MouseMoveEvent
defs.docs:
The `MouseMoveEvent` is fired when a pointing device (usually a mouse)
 is moved while over an element.

defs.name: MouseOverEvent
defs.docs:
The `MouseOverEvent` is fired when a pointing device (usually a mouse)
 is moved onto the element that has the listener attached or onto one of its children.

defs.name: MouseOutEvent
defs.docs:
The `MouseOutEvent` is fired when a pointing device (usually a mouse)
 is moved off the element that has the listener attached or off one of its children.

defs.name: IPointerEvent
defs.docs:
The `IPointerEvent` interface represents the state of a DOM event produced by a pointer
 such as the geometry of the contact point, the device type that generated the event, the
 amount of pressure that was applied on the contact surface, etc.

defs.name: pointer_id
defs.docs: Returns a unique identifier for the pointer causing the event.

defs.name: width
defs.docs: Returns the width, in CSS pixels, of the contact geometry of the pointer.

defs.name: height
defs.docs: Returns the height, in CSS pixels, of the contact geometry of the pointer.

defs.name: pressure
defs.docs: Returns the normalized pressure of the pointer in the range [0, 1]

defs.name: tangential_pressure
defs.docs:
Returns the normalized tangential pressure of the pointer in the range [-1, 1], where 0 is
 the hardware's neutral position

defs.name: tilt_x
defs.docs:
Returns the angle, in the range of [-90, 90] degrees, between the Y-Z plane and the plane
 containing the transducer (e.g. pen stylus) and the Y axis.

defs.name: tilt_y
defs.docs:
Returns the angle, in the range of [-90, 90] degrees, between the X-Z plane and the plane
 containing the transducer (e.g. pen stylus) and the X axis.

defs.name: twist
defs.docs:
Returns the clockwise rotation, in the range of [0, 359] degrees, of
 the transducer (e.g. pen stylus) around it's own major axis

defs.name: pointer_type
defs.docs: Indicates the device type that caused the event.

defs.name: is_primary
defs.docs: Indicates if the pointer represents the primary pointer of this pointer type

defs.name: PointerEvent
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IPointerEvent](trait.IPointerEvent.html)
 interface.

defs.name: PointerOverEvent
defs.docs:
The `PointerOverEvent` is fired when a pointing device is moved into
 a element's hit test boundaries.

defs.name: PointerEnterEvent
defs.docs:
The `PointerEnterEvent` is fired when a pointing device is moved into
 the hit test boundaries of an element or its descendants. This event does not bubble.

defs.name: PointerDownEvent
defs.docs: The `PointerDownEvent` is fired when a pointer becomes active

defs.name: PointerMoveEvent
defs.docs: The `PointerMoveEvent` is fired when a pointer changes coordinates

defs.name: get_coalesced_events
defs.docs: Returns the sequence of all `PointerEvent` instances that were coalesced into the dispatched `PointerMoveEvent`.

defs.name: PointerUpEvent
defs.docs: The `PointerUpEvent` is fired when a pointer is no longer active

defs.name: PointerCancelEvent
defs.docs:
The `PointerCancelEvent` is fired when a pointer will no longer produce events
 (for example the device is deactivated), or if the pointer starts a gesture after a pointerdown event
 (for example panning, zooming, or drag and drop)

defs.name: PointerOutEvent
defs.docs:
The `PointerOutEvent` is fired when the pointer moves out of the hit test boundaries of an element.
 This can include when a finger leaves a touch screen or a pen leaves the detectable hover range.

defs.name: PointerLeaveEvent
defs.docs:
The `PointerLeaveEvent` is fired when the pointer moves out of the hit test boundaries
 of an element and it's descendants. This can include when a finger leaves a touch screen
 or a pen leaves the detectable hover range. This event does not bubble.

defs.name: GotPointerCaptureEvent
defs.docs: The `GotPointerCaptureEvent` fires when an element receives pointer capture

defs.name: LostPointerCaptureEvent
defs.docs: The `LostPointerCaptureEvent` fires when an element loses pointer capture

defs.name: IProgressEvent
defs.docs:
The `IProgressEvent` interface represents progress-related
 events.

defs.name: length_computable
defs.docs: Indicates whether the progress is measureable.

defs.name: loaded
defs.docs: Returns the amount of work already performed by the underlying process.

defs.name: total
defs.docs: Returns the total amount of work that the underlying process will perform.

defs.name: ProgressRelatedEvent
defs.docs:
A reference to a JavaScript object which implements the [IProgressEvent](trait.IProgressEvent.html)
 interface.

defs.name: ProgressEvent
defs.docs: The `ProgressEvent` is fired to indicate that an operation is in progress.

defs.name: ProgressLoadEvent
defs.docs: The `ProgressLoadEvent` is fired when progress has successful finished.

defs.name: LoadStartEvent
defs.docs: The `LoadStartEvent` is fired when progress has begun.

defs.name: LoadEndEvent
defs.docs:
The `LoadEndEvent` is fired when progress has stopped,
 e.g. after `ProgressErrorEvent`, `ProgressAbortEvent`
 or `ProgressLoadEvent` have been dispatched.

defs.name: ProgressAbortEvent
defs.docs: The `ProgressAbortEvent` is fired when the progress has been aborted.

defs.name: ProgressErrorEvent
defs.docs: The `ProgressErrorEvent` is fired when the progress has failed.

defs.name: SocketCloseEvent
defs.docs: A SocketCloseEvent is sent to clients using WebSockets when the connection is closed.

defs.name: code
defs.docs: Returns the close code sent by the server.

defs.name: reason
defs.docs: Returns the reason the server closed the connection. This is specific to the particular server and sub-protocol.

defs.name: was_clean
defs.docs: Returns whether or not the connection was cleanly closed.

defs.name: SocketErrorEvent
defs.docs:
The error event is fired when an error occurred; the exact circumstances vary,
 events by this name are used from a variety of APIs.

defs.name: SocketOpenEvent
defs.docs: An open event informs the target that a data connection, has been established.

defs.name: Text
defs.docs: Text message

defs.name: Blob
defs.docs: Binary message received as a blob

defs.name: ArrayBuffer
defs.docs: Binary message received as an array buffer

defs.name: SocketMessageData
defs.docs:
Represents the types of data which can be received on a web socket. Messages
 are transmitted tagged as either binary or text: text messages are always
 received as strings. Binary messages may be received as either blobs or array
 buffers as preferred by the receiver. This choice is indicated via the
 `binary_type` field on the web socket.

defs.name: into_text
defs.docs: Try to receive the message as text

defs.name: into_blob
defs.docs: Try to receive the message as a binary blob

defs.name: into_array_buffer
defs.docs: Try to receive the message as an array buffer

defs.name: IMessageEvent
defs.docs: The MessageEvent interface represents a message received by a target object.

defs.name: Data
defs.docs: The type of data received with this MessageEvent

defs.name: data
defs.docs: The data sent by the message emitter.

defs.name: origin
defs.docs: A string representing the origin of the message emitter.

defs.name: last_event_id
defs.docs: A string representing a unique ID for the event.

defs.name: source
defs.docs:
A MessageEventSource (which can be a WindowProxy, MessagePort, or ServiceWorker object)
 representing the message emitter.

defs.name: ports
defs.docs:
An array of MessagePort objects representing the ports associated with the channel the
 message is being sent through (where appropriate, e.g. in channel messaging or when sending
 a message to a shared worker).

defs.name: SocketMessageEvent
defs.docs: A message event informs a WebSocket object that a message has been received.

defs.name: IParentNode
defs.docs:
The `ParentNode` mixin contains methods and properties
 that are common to all types of `Node` objects that can
 have children.

defs.name: query_selector
defs.docs:
Returns the first element that is a descendant of the element on which it is
 invoked that matches the specified group of selectors.

defs.name: query_selector_all
defs.docs:
Returns a non-live [NodeList](struct.NodeList.html) of all elements descended
 from the element on which it is invoked that matches the specified group of CSS selectors.

defs.name: INonElementParentNode
defs.docs:
The `INonElementParentNode` mixin contains methods and properties
 that are common to `Document` and `DocumentFragment`.

defs.name: get_element_by_id
defs.docs:
Returns a reference to the element by its ID; the ID is a string which can
 be used to uniquely identify the element, found in the HTML `id` attribute.

defs.name: HtmlCollection
defs.docs:
The `HtmlCollection` interface represents a generic collection
 (array-like object similar to arguments) of elements (in document order)
 and offers methods and properties for selecting from the list.
 
 An `HtmlCollection` in the HTML DOM is live; it is automatically
 updated when the underlying document is changed.
 
 [(JavaScript docs)](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/HTMLCollection)

defs.name: len
defs.docs: Returns the number of elements in the collection.

defs.name: item
defs.docs: Returns an element from an `HtmlCollection` by index.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs: Returns an iterator over the collection.

defs.name: IChildNode
defs.docs:
The `ChildNode` interface contains methods that are particular to `Node`
 objects that can have a parent.

defs.name: remove
defs.docs: The `ChildNode.remove()` method removes the object from the tree it belongs to.

defs.name: ConversionError
defs.docs:
A structure denoting a conversion error encountered during
 serialization or deserialization.

defs.name: Serde
defs.docs:
A newtype which makes it possible to pass a value which implements
 Serde's `Serializable` into the [js!](macro.js.html) macro.

defs.name: serde
defs.docs: A module with serde-related APIs.

defs.name: web
defs.docs: A module with bindings to the Web APIs.

defs.name: error
defs.docs: A module containing error types.

defs.name: html_element
defs.docs: A module containing HTML DOM elements.

defs.name: event
defs.docs: A module containing JavaScript DOM events.

defs.name: unstable
defs.docs:
A module containing stable counterparts to currently
 unstable Rust features.

defs.name: traits
defs.docs: A module containing reexports of all of our interface traits.
